          "body": "Verses 7-12 contain some of the most beautiful language in the chapter — and in the whole book of Job. The rhetorical questions of verses 7-9 stack up a cosmic four-directional portrait of God's incomprehensibility: higher than heaven, deeper than Sheol, longer than the earth, broader than the sea. This is genuine orthodox theology. The same doxological tradition appears in Psalm 139:7-12, Isaiah 40:12-26, and Romans 11:33-36. God's ways are past finding out; His knowledge has no limit. Zophar is not wrong about God. He is wrong about what this means for Job. The divine transcendence argument is deployed not to comfort Job with the thought that the same incomprehensible God is present with him in his suffering, but to shut Job's self-defense down permanently. Verse 12 — the proverb about the wild donkey's foal — is the logical conclusion: it is as impossible for Job to become wise enough to assess his own moral state as it is for a wild ass's colt to be born a human being. Transcendence becomes a blunt instrument."
